:"1428","1427":"1427","about 1450":"about 1450","Chelwood, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Chelwood, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Chelwood, Somerset, England":"Chelwood, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","harlyn, cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tregoz","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Cornish (Cornwall and Devon): habitational name from Treago in Crantock (Cornwall). The placename derives from Middle Cornish <i>tre</i> ‘estate, farmstead’ + uncertain final element.","Altered form of French   Tricot   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname. It was reportedly brought to North America from England. Today it is found mainly in PA and OH. Compare   Trago  .","History: This surname (see 2 above) is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America."],"variants":[{"name":"Tricot","meanings":["(2010: NA)","French:","nickname from a diminutive of <i>trique</i> ‘cudgel’."]},{"name":"Trago","meanings":["Variant of   Trego  , a surname of Cornish and French origin. In the US, it is found mainly in PA and OH."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Richard Tregoz was born in 1427, in Chelwood, Somerset, England, United Kingdom as the son of Richard Tregose. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Margery Glyn. He died in 1456, at the age of 29."},"et":{"1427–1456":"1427–1456","1428–Female":"1428–Surnud","1450–Male":"1450–Surnud","1452–1507":"1452–1507","1456–1485":"1456–1485","1392–Male":"1392–Surnud","1456":"1456","1485":"1485","1452":"1452","1450":"1450","1392":"1392","1507":"1507","about 1452":"umbes 1452","1428":"1428","1427":"1427","about 1450":"umbes 1450","Chelwood, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Chelwood, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Chelwood, Somerset, England":"Chelwood, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","harlyn, cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England"},"fi":{"1427–1456":"1427–1456","1428–Female":"1428–Kuollut","1450–Male":"1450–Kuollut","1452–1507":"1452–1507","1456–1485":"1456–1485","1392–Male":"1392–Kuollut","1456":"1456","1485":"1485","1452":"1452","1450":"1450","1392":"1392","1507":"1507","about 1452":"noin 1452","1428":"1428","1427":"1427","about 1450":"noin 1450","Chelwood, Somerset, England, United King